What is Canary Deployment?
        Definition

        Canary Deployment is a release strategy where:
            👉 You release a new version to a small group of users first, and then gradually roll it out to everyone.

        🧠 Simple idea:

            Test the new version on a few users before giving it to all users

        🐤 Why is it called “Canary”?

            In old coal mines:

                Miners carried canary birds
                If toxic gas appeared → bird reacted first

        👉 Early warning system

        ➡️ Same idea in software:

            Small group = “canary users”
            Detect issues early
        🔄 How it works (Step-by-step)
            Current version is running (stable)
            New version is deployed to 5–10% users
        Monitor:
            errors
            performance
            If everything is good:
                Increase to 25% → 50% → 100%
            If something fails:
                Stop rollout immediately ❌

        🌍 Real-world example
                📱 App update (like Instagram/WhatsApp)

        New feature released to a small group of users
        Others still see old version

        👉 If no issues:

            Feature is released to everyone
            🛒 E-commerce website
                10% users see:
                    👉 new checkout page
                90% users see:
                    👉 old checkout page

        👉 Compare:

        Which works better?
            Any bugs?
                ⚖️ Canary vs Blue-Green (Quick understanding)
        Feature	Canary	Blue-Green
        Release	Gradual	Instant switch
        Users	Small % first	All users at once
        Risk	Very low	Medium
        Rollback	Stop rollout	Switch back

        💻 Simple Python Simulation

        import random

        def old_version():
            return "Old Version"

        def new_version():
            return "New Version"

        def route_user():
            # 20% users get new version
            if random.random() < 0.2:
                return new_version()
            else:
                return old_version()

        for _ in range(10):
            print(route_user())

        👉 Some users get new version, others don’t

        🎯 Benefits
            🛡️ Reduced risk
            🔍 Early bug detection
            📊 Real user feedback
            🚀 Smooth rollout
        ⚠️ Challenges
                ❌ More complex to manage
                ❌ Needs monitoring tools
                ❌ Requires traffic control

        🌍 More real-world analogies
            🍽️ Restaurant
                    Chef tests new dish on a few customers
                    If they like it → add to full menu

            🎓 Classroom
                Teacher tests new teaching method on one group
                If effective → apply to whole class

            🔥 Key Difference (Simple)
            Canary → gradual rollout 🐤
            Blue-Green → instant switch 🔄
