What are some design patterns in microservices?
    1. API Gateway Pattern
            Definition

            A single entry point that handles all client requests and routes them to appropriate microservices.

            🧠 Why needed?
                    Avoid direct communication with many services
                    Centralize authentication, logging, routing
            🌍 Real-world example:
                📱 Food Delivery App
                    Client calls one API
                    Gateway routes to:
                            User Service
                            Order Service
                            Payment Service

            👉 Like a receptionist directing you

    ✅ 2. Circuit Breaker Pattern

            Stops calling a failing service to prevent system failure.

            🌍 Example:
                🛒 E-commerce
                Payment service is down
            Circuit breaker:
                👉 Stops further calls
                👉 Shows “Try again later”

            👉 Like electrical fuse protecting devices
    ✅ 3. Service Discovery Pattern
            Services dynamically find and communicate with each other.

        🧠 Problem:

            Services keep changing (scaling, containers)

        🌍 Example:
                🚕 Ride App
                Driver service instances keep changing
                App finds available driver via registry

        👉 Like Google Maps finding nearby drivers

✅ 4. Database per Service Pattern

        Each microservice has its own database

        🧠 Why?
                Avoid tight coupling
                Independent scaling
        🌍 Example:
                🛒 E-commerce
                User Service → User DB
                Order Service → Order DB
                Payment Service → Payment DB

        👉 No sharing database directly

✅ 5. Saga Pattern (Distributed Transactions)

        Manages transactions across multiple services using steps and compensations

        🌍 Example:
            🛒 Order Placement

        Steps:

            Create order
            Deduct payment
            Reserve inventory

        👉 If payment fails:

                Cancel order
                Rollback inventory

        👉 Like booking a trip:

                If flight fails → cancel hotel
✅ 6. Event-Driven Pattern

        Services communicate using events instead of direct calls

        🌍 Example:
                🛍️ Order System
                Order placed → event triggered
        Services react:
                Payment service processes payment
                Notification service sends email

        👉 Like YouTube notification system

✅ 7. Strangler Fig Pattern

    Gradually replace a monolithic system with microservices

        🌍 Example:
            🏦 Banking system
            Old system running
            New services replace parts step-by-step

👉 Like a plant growing around a tree and replacing it

✅ 8. Config Server Pattern

    Centralized configuration for all services

    🌍 Example:
    Change DB URL in one place
    All services update automatically

    👉 Like central control panel

✅ 9. Bulkhead Pattern

    Isolate failures so one service doesn’t affect others

    🌍 Example:
    🎬 Streaming app
    Video service crashes
    Recommendation service still works

    👉 Like ship compartments (one leak ≠ sink entire ship)

✅ 10. Canary Deployment Pattern

        Release new version to small group first

        🌍 Example:
                📱 App update
                10% users get new feature
                If safe → roll out to all

👉 Like testing medicine on small group first
