How do you handle inter-service communication failure?
    Handling inter-service communication failure (in microservices or distributed systems) is less about preventing failure entirely—and more about designing for it.
    Failures will happen (timeouts, network issues, partial outages), so your system should stay resilient.

    🔁 1. Retry Mechanisms (with Backoff)

                When a request fails due to transient issues:

                    Retry automatically (but limit attempts)
                    Use exponential backoff (e.g., 100ms → 200ms → 400ms)
                    Add jitter to avoid retry storms

                👉 Avoid retrying on permanent errors (like 4xx).

⏱   ️ 2. Timeouts Everywhere

        Never let a service wait indefinitely:

            Set connection timeout + read timeout
            Fail fast so upstream services don’t pile up

    🔌 3. Circuit Breaker Pattern

            Prevents cascading failures:

                If a service fails repeatedly → “open” the circuit
                Temporarily stop calling it
                Periodically test recovery (half-open state)

                Popular libraries:
                    Resilience4j (Java)
                    Hystrix (legacy but widely known)

        🧯 4. Fallback Strategies

                When a dependent service fails:

                Return cached data
                Return default values
                Degrade gracefully (e.g., show partial UI)

                Example:

                If recommendation service fails → still show product list without recommendations

        📬 5. Asynchronous Communication

                Avoid tight coupling:

                Use message queues (e.g., Kafka, RabbitMQ)
                Event-driven architecture reduces direct dependency

                Benefits:

                    Better resilience
                    Natural buffering during spikes/failures
        🧠 6. Idempotency

                Ensure retries don’t cause issues:

                Same request → same result (no duplicate side effects)
                Use idempotency keys for POST operations

        📊 7. Monitoring & Observability

            You can’t fix what you can’t see:

                Metrics (latency, error rates)
                Distributed tracing (e.g., OpenTelemetry)
                Centralized logging

            Set alerts for:

                Increased failure rate
                Timeout spikes
        🚦 8. Bulkheads (Isolation)

                Prevent one failure from taking down everything:

                Separate thread pools / resource pools per service
                Limit concurrent calls to dependencies
        🧪 9. Chaos Testing

                    Actively test failure scenarios:

                    Kill services randomly
                    Inject latency
                    Validate system resilience

        Tools:

            Chaos Monkey
            Gremlin

        🧩 10. Graceful Degradation Strategy

            Define what still works when something breaks:

                Core features > non-essential features
                Design UX accordingly
                🧭 Real-world mindset

        Instead of:
            “How do we prevent failure?”

        Think:
            “What happens when this service fails?”
