How do you test microservice?
    Testing microservices isn’t just “write some unit tests”—you’re validating a distributed system, where failures, latency, and contracts matter just as much as logic.

    A good strategy uses multiple layers of testing, each catching different kinds of issues:

    🧪 1. Unit Testing (Fast & Isolated)

                Test individual functions/classes inside a service.

                Mock external dependencies (DB, APIs)
                Focus on business logic
                Run on every commit

    Example:

        Validate pricing logic
        Check validation rules

    👉 Tools: JUnit, Mockito, Jest, pytest

🔗 2. Integration Testing (Service + Dependencies)

        Test how your service interacts with real components:

        Database
        Cache (Redis)
        Message brokers

        Instead of mocking everything:

                Use test containers or in-memory DBs

        Example:

            Save order → verify DB entry
            Publish event → verify queue receives it

🤝 3. Contract Testing (Critical for Microservices)

            Ensures services agree on API formats.

            Two main approaches:

                Consumer-driven contracts
                Schema validation (OpenAPI, JSON Schema)

            Popular tools:

                Pact

            Why it matters:
                Prevents breaking changes between services without needing full integration tests.

🌐 4. End-to-End (E2E) Testing

            Test the full system flow across services.

            Runs in staging-like environment
            Covers real workflows

            Example:

                User places order → payment → inventory → confirmation

            👉 These are:

                    Slower
                    Fewer in number
                    High value
⚡ 5. Performance Testing

        Test how services behave under load.

        Latency
        Throughput
        Resource usage

        Tools:

            JMeter
            k6
            Gatling
💥 6. Resilience / Failure Testing

            Microservices must handle failure gracefully.

            Test:

            Timeouts
            Service unavailability
            Network latency

            Techniques:

            Chaos testing (kill services, inject delay)
            Simulate downstream failures
🔄 7. API Testing

            Focus specifically on service endpoints:

            Request/response validation
            Status codes
            Edge cases

            Tools:

            Postman / Newman
            REST Assured
🧱 8. Test Pyramid for Microservices

            A healthy balance looks like:

                    E2E Tests        (few)
                 Integration Tests   (some)
              Unit + Contract Tests  (many)
🧠 Best Practices
            ✅ Test in isolation first

            Avoid relying on full system for every test.

            ✅ Use CI/CD pipelines

            Run:

            Unit + contract tests on every commit
            Integration/E2E on merge or nightly
            ✅ Use realistic test data

            Avoid only “happy path” data.

            ✅ Mock wisely
            Mock external services in unit tests
            Avoid over-mocking in integration tests
            ✅ Version your APIs

            So contract tests stay reliable

        🚨 Common Mistakes
            Too many E2E tests → slow pipelines
            No contract testing → breaking integrations
            Ignoring failure scenarios
            Testing only “happy paths”
